| Biomarker                       | Desired Direction | Threshold Type Needed | Suggested Weight | Literature-Based Justification                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             |
| ------------------------------- | ----------------- | --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| CRP (C-Reactive Protein)        | Lower is better   | High threshold mainly | 15               | CRP is a canonical systemic inflammation marker strongly associated with endothelial dysfunction and cardiovascular event risk. Elevated CRP reflects vascular injury and inflammatory burden relevant to spaceflight-induced physiological stress. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19047567/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19047567/) |
| Fibrinogen                      | Lower is better   | High threshold mainly | 12               | Fibrinogen is a coagulation-associated acute phase protein. Elevated fibrinogen increases thrombosis risk, blood viscosity, and cardiovascular strain. Hypercoagulability is a major concern in microgravity physiology. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22527940/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22527940/)                            |
| Haptoglobin                     | Lower is better   | High threshold mainly | 10               | Haptoglobin is an acute phase reactant involved in hemoglobin scavenging and oxidative stress regulation. Elevated haptoglobin reflects inflammatory and oxidative vascular stress associated with radiation exposure and endothelial injury. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24858715/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24858715/)       |
| Alpha-2-Macroglobulin (A2M)     | Balanced          | Both low and high     | 8                | Alpha-2-macroglobulin regulates protease activity and inflammatory signaling. Both suppression and excessive elevation may indicate dysregulated immune or coagulation responses affecting vascular homeostasis. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15183785/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15183785/)                                    |
| AGP (Alpha-1-Acid Glycoprotein) | Lower is better   | High threshold mainly | 8                | AGP is a major acute phase glycoprotein elevated during chronic systemic inflammation. Elevated AGP correlates with cardiovascular disease risk and persistent inflammatory activation. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15576483/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15576483/)                                                             |
| PF4 (Platelet Factor 4)         | Lower is better   | High threshold mainly | 15               | PF4 is a platelet activation marker linked to thrombotic activity and endothelial dysfunction. Elevated PF4 suggests increased clotting potential and platelet aggregation risk during physiologic stress. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17627478/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17627478/)                                          |
| L-Selectin (CD62L)              | Balanced          | Both low and high     | 10               | L-selectin regulates leukocyte adhesion and endothelial interaction. Dysregulated levels indicate abnormal immune-endothelial activation and vascular inflammatory stress. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10739650/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10739650/)                                                                          |
| Fetuin-A                        | Balanced          | Both low and high     | 12               | Fetuin-A modulates vascular calcification and metabolic regulation. Both reduced and excessive levels have been associated with cardiovascular dysfunction, insulin resistance, and inflammatory disease states. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20360910/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20360910/)                                    |
| SAP (Serum Amyloid P Component) | Lower is better   | High threshold mainly | 10               | SAP is an acute phase inflammatory protein associated with chronic inflammatory activation and tissue remodeling. Elevated SAP reflects persistent systemic inflammatory burden relevant to cardiovascular stress monitoring. [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11895757/](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11895757/)                       |
